I just moved to NYC last month, and I wanted to explore MTA stations. For those who want to up their game with data visualization, this is a tutorial for a versatile interactive map. Given the longitudinal and latitudinal data, you could easily create a beautiful map on point.

First we import necessary packages. `folium` lets us visualize our data on a Leaflet map using Python.

```python
# import necessary packages
import pandas as pd
import folium
```

Now, we will import the data. Here, we will be looking at MTA stations data.

```python
# import data
data = pd.read_csv("http://web.mta.info/developers/data/nyct/subway/StationEntrances.csv")
df = data.groupby('Station_Name')[['Station_Name', 'Station_Latitude','Station_Longitude']].head(1)
```

Now, this is where the magic happens. First we graph the map of New York. We will be using my favorite theme `"cartodbdark_matter"`, but there are other options available. Then, we will add markers for each location.

```python
# this gives us the map of New York
nyc_mta = folium.Map(location=[40.738, -73.88],
                        zoom_start=10,
                        tiles="cartodbdark_matter")

# this snippet of code graphs multiple points on the map
df.apply(lambda row:folium.CircleMarker(location=[row["Station_Latitude"], row["Station_Longitude"]], 
                                        radius = 10, color = 'yellow') 
         .add_to(nyc_mta), axis=1)
```
